      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Brisbane Property With Leased or PPA Solar Panels
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Leased solar and power purchase agreements attach a long-term contract to your roof. Here is how Brisbane sellers handle buyer takeover, buyout at settlement, and the disclosure obligations vendors regularly miss.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The Brisbane rooftop solar boom of the past decade was sold to homeowners in two flavours. The first was the straightforward owned system: the household paid for the panels, kept the feed-in tariff, and treated them as a fixed improvement to the property. The second was the leased system or solar power purchase agreement (PPA), where a third-party provider installed and owned the panels and the household paid a monthly lease fee or bought the generated electricity at a contracted rate. The owned-solar story has been told well. The leased and PPA story has not, and Brisbane sellers regularly arrive at a sale campaign without realising the contract on their roof is going to shape the negotiation.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the practical decisions a Brisbane seller faces when there is a leased solar system or PPA on the property. It covers the three exit paths at settlement, the disclosure obligations that catch vendors out, the conversations to have with the solar provider before listing, and the pricing reality of a contract that follows the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Owned, leased, and PPA: the distinction that matters</h2>
      <p>Most sellers who installed solar in the past decade have an owned system. The household paid an upfront price (typically four to twelve thousand dollars at the time, more for premium installations), the panels and inverter belong to them, and at settlement they transfer with the property as a fixture. There is no ongoing contract, no buyer takeover, and no buyout to negotiate. Disclosure is straightforward: the system is an inclusion, the warranty paperwork hands across, and the buyer becomes the new system owner.</p>

      <p>A leased solar system is different. A finance or solar provider owns the equipment. The household signed a fixed-term lease (commonly seven, ten, or fifteen years) and pays a monthly fee for the use of the panels. The household keeps the generated electricity but does not own the equipment until the lease term ends, if at all.</p>

      <p>A solar power purchase agreement (PPA) is a third structure. The provider installs and owns the panels, and the household agrees to buy the electricity those panels generate at a contracted rate (often slightly below the household's standard retail rate). The household pays for what is produced rather than a flat monthly fee, but the contract is still long-term and still attaches the equipment to the property.</p>

      <p>From the buyer's perspective at a Brisbane open home, all three look identical: panels on the roof, an inverter on the wall. From the contract perspective, the difference is large. An owned system is a benefit. A leased system or PPA is a long-term obligation, and Queensland law treats it accordingly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The three exit paths at settlement</h2>
      <p>If your Brisbane property has a leased system or PPA, there are exactly three ways the contract is resolved at settlement. The choice is the seller's, in consultation with the buyer and the solar provider, but the path needs to be decided well before contracts are exchanged.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Path one: pay out the contract before settlement.</strong> The seller contacts the solar provider, requests an early-termination or buyout figure, and pays it from the sale proceeds at settlement. The panels become unencumbered and transfer to the buyer as part of the property. This is the cleanest path for the buyer and the simplest to communicate during the campaign. It is also usually the most expensive for the seller, because early-termination figures are designed to recover the provider's expected revenue across the remaining term.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Path two: negotiate a buyer-funded buyout.</strong> The seller and buyer agree, as a special condition of the contract, that the buyer will pay the buyout figure (or contribute to it) in addition to the purchase price. Functionally similar to path one, but the cost lands on the buyer rather than the seller. This works in a strong market with a motivated buyer and a reasonable buyout figure. It does not work well when the buyout figure is large or the market is soft.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Path three: buyer takeover of the contract.</strong> The buyer agrees to step into the existing lease or PPA on the same terms as the seller, with the solar provider's formal consent. The provider runs a credit check on the buyer, the documentation is updated, and the contract continues without a payout. This is the cheapest path for the seller but introduces a new variable into the campaign: the buyer's willingness to take over a long-term contract they did not choose.</p>

      <p>Each path has a place. The right choice depends on the buyout figure, the remaining term, the strength of the local market, and the buyer profile. A property with an eighteen-month-old fifteen-year lease and a fifteen-thousand-dollar buyout figure faces a different decision to one with a four-year-old seven-year contract and a three-thousand-dollar buyout.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Get the buyout figure before listing</h2>
      <p>The single most useful step a Brisbane seller can take before launching a campaign with a leased system or PPA is to request the current buyout figure from the solar provider in writing. This document tells you, on the day, exactly how much it would cost to pay out the contract at settlement. The figure changes month by month as the contract amortises, so the number you got two years ago at signing is not the number you need now.</p>

      <p>Most providers will issue a buyout statement on request, sometimes through a dedicated process for property sales. The statement will typically show the principal balance, any early-termination fees, the calculation method, and an expiry date for the quoted figure. Sellers should also ask for the takeover process documentation: what credit checks the new occupier will need to pass, how the contract is novated, and the timing involved.</p>

      <p>Without this information, the seller goes into the campaign blind. A buyer asks at the second inspection what the lease costs to take over, the seller does not have an answer, and the buyer reads the silence as a problem. With the information in hand, the seller and agent can frame the conversation accurately from day one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure: the obligation Brisbane sellers regularly miss</h2>
      <p>A leased solar system or PPA is not a generic inclusion. It is a long-term financial commitment that runs with the property unless paid out. Queensland sellers have disclosure obligations under the contract of sale and under broader consumer protection law that apply to material facts a reasonable buyer would want to know. A multi-year electricity supply contract or panel lease easily clears that bar.</p>

      <p>The right approach is to disclose the agreement, the remaining term, the monthly payment or rate, the buyout figure as currently quoted, and the takeover process, before contracts are exchanged. The disclosure should be in writing, included in the seller's solicitor file, and ideally referenced in the contract itself as a special condition. Burying it in fixtures and inclusions paperwork or assuming the buyer will work it out is a misrepresentation risk.</p>

      <p>The cost of poor disclosure here is not just legal. A buyer who discovers a leased system mid-contract will at minimum demand a price reduction equal to the buyout figure and at worst will use the discovery to terminate. Both outcomes are avoidable with a thirty-minute disclosure conversation up front.</p>

      <p>For broader context on Queensland disclosure obligations, see our notes on <a href="/insights/seller-disclosure-obligations-queensland" style="color:#f5d07a;">seller disclosure obligations in Queensland</a> and on <a href="/insights/material-fact-property-sale-queensland" style="color:#f5d07a;">what counts as a material fact in a Queensland property sale</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pricing the contract into the campaign</h2>
      <p>A leased system or PPA has a price effect on the campaign whether or not the seller acknowledges it. Buyers price risk and obligation. A property that comes with a fifteen-thousand-dollar buyout requirement effectively sells for fifteen thousand dollars less than the same property without one, unless the seller absorbs the cost or the buyer values the cheap electricity enough to neutralise it.</p>

      <p>The seller has three options for handling this in the price strategy. The first is to pay out the contract before listing, market the property with an unencumbered owned solar system, and lift the price guide accordingly. The second is to disclose the contract and the buyout, accept that the price guide will sit slightly below an unencumbered comparable, and let the market price the obligation. The third is to disclose the contract, position takeover as the default, and accept that the buyer pool narrows to those willing to inherit a long-term agreement.</p>

      <p>None of these is universally right. A seller with a small buyout and plenty of contract term remaining might find takeover works because the buyer benefits from cheap power. A seller with a large buyout and short remaining term often finds payout is the cleanest answer. The numbers tell the story; what matters is running them before the campaign starts.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common Brisbane scenarios</h2>
      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Recently signed long-term lease.</strong> A seller signed a fifteen-year lease two years ago and is selling earlier than expected. The buyout figure is high (often above ten thousand dollars), the remaining term is long, and few Brisbane buyers are enthusiastic about taking over an unfamiliar thirteen-year obligation. Pay-out is usually the answer; absorb the cost from the sale proceeds and present the property cleanly.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mid-term lease with reasonable economics.</strong> A seller is six years into a ten-year lease with four years to run and a moderate monthly payment. Buyer takeover is feasible because the remaining term is short enough for buyers to digest, and the monthly cost is offset by the generated electricity. The seller's choice tends to depend on market strength: in a hot market, takeover; in a cool one, payout.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">PPA with attractive electricity rate.</strong> A seller has a PPA where the contracted electricity rate is significantly below current retail. The PPA itself becomes a benefit for the buyer, not a burden, provided the rate remains attractive across the remaining term. Disclosure remains essential, but the framing in the campaign can be positive. Buyers who run the numbers see lower bills, not a long-term obligation.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Lease with provider in financial difficulty.</strong> If the solar provider has been through administration, restructured, or sold its book to another party, the contract may be more complicated than the original paperwork suggests. The seller's solicitor should confirm the current contract holder, the buyout process under the new entity, and whether the takeover route is still operational. This scenario justifies extra time and a careful approach.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical pre-listing checklist</h2>
      <p>1. Identify the system on your property: owned, leased, or PPA. Check the original paperwork, your monthly bills, and any direct debits to a solar provider. 2. If leased or PPA, request the current buyout figure in writing from the provider. 3. Request the takeover process documentation, including credit-check requirements for the buyer. 4. Speak with your solicitor about disclosure wording for the contract of sale. 5. Decide your preferred path (payout, buyer-funded buyout, takeover) and the fallback. 6. Brief your agent so the contract is part of the conversation from the first inspection, not the last. 7. Update the listing description to reference solar accurately, without overclaiming on cost savings or undersells on obligation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line</h2>
      <p>Leased solar systems and PPAs are increasingly common on Brisbane rooftops, and they will continue to surface in sale campaigns as the original ten- and fifteen-year contracts work their way through the cycle. The contract on your roof is a real obligation, but it is also a manageable one if the seller takes the steps before listing rather than after the buyer's solicitor finds it. Get the buyout figure in writing. Decide the path. Disclose accurately. Let the buyer make an informed decision rather than a confused one. Sellers who do this convert the contract from a campaign liability into a non-issue. Sellers who do not usually pay for the silence at settlement.</p>

